  "prompt": "Why is AC current more dangerous than DC current?",
  "response": "AC (alternating current) can be more dangerous than DC (direct current) for several reasons related to its physiological effects on the human body and electrical properties:\n\n1. **Frequency and Muscle Stimulation**: AC current at certain frequencies (most notably around 50-60 Hz, which is common for household AC) can cause a phenomenon known as tetany, where muscles contract uncontrollably and can freeze in place. This can be particularly dangerous if the current flows through the chest, as it can affect the heart and lung muscles, potentially leading to ventricular fibrillation or respiratory paralysis.\n\n2. **Perception and Reaction**: AC is often perceived as more painful and causes a stronger reaction in the body compared to DC. This heightened perception and the muscle contraction can make it more difficult to release an object conducting AC electricity. DC tends to cause a single contraction and may lead to being thrown away from the source, whereas AC might clamp the muscles and prevent letting go.\n\n3. **Skin Impedance**: AC can lower the impedance of the skin over time, allowing more current to pass through the body. DC typically causes the skin to maintain higher resistance due to electrochemical effects.\n\n4. **Electrochemical Effects**: AC reverses current direction frequently (for example, 60 times per second in a 60 Hz system), which can minimize certain electrochemical effects that can cause tissue damage, while DC can cause more localized burns and effects due to unidirectional current flow.\n\n5. **Power Systems**: AC is used in most power distribution systems, making it more common in environments where human contact with electrical systems might occur.\n\nIt should be noted that both AC and DC can be lethal at sufficient levels of current (generally greater than 30 mA for AC and 300-500 mA for DC) and appropriate safety measures should always be in place when working with or near electrical systems.",
